FOOT AND MOUTH DISEASE - RUSSIA: (ZABAYKALSKY) OIE, SEROTYPE O, SEA
TOPOTYPE
****************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Mon 21 Mar 2011
Source: OIE, WAHID (World Animal Health Information Database), weekly
disease information 2011; 24(12) [edited]
<http://web.oie.int/wahis/public.php?page=single_report&pop=1&reportid=10387>


Foot-and-mouth disease, Russia
------------------------------
Information received on (and dated) 21 Mar 2011 from Dr Nicolay
Vlasov, CVO, Veterinary Services, Ministry of Agriculture and Food,
Moscow, Russia

Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Start date: 13 Mar 2011
Date of 1st confirmation of the event: 18 Mar 2011
Report date: 21 Mar 2011
Date submitted to OIE: 21 Mar 2011
Reason for notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 11 Oct 2010
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: Foot and mouth disease virus (SEA topotype)
Serotype O
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, Laboratory (advanced)
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country

New outbreaks
Summary of outbreaks
Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak 1: Village Us't-Imalka, Ononsky, [Zabaykalsky Krai]
Date of start of the outbreak: 13 Mar 2011
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals
Species: cattle
Susceptible: 1518
Cases: 117
Deaths: 0
Destroyed: 0
Slaughtered: 0

Species: swine
Susceptible: 73
Cases: 1
Deaths: 0
Destroyed: 0
Slaughtered: 0

Species: sheep
Susceptible: 2865
Cases: 0
Deaths: 0
Destroyed: 0
Slaughtered: 0

Affected population: a private holding

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: unknown or
inconclusive
Epidemiological comments: the village of Us't-Imalka is located 18 km
[11 mi] from the Mongolian border in the buffer anti-FMD zone where
the authorities carry out vaccination of cattle, sheep, and goats
against the FMD serotypes O, A, and Asia-1. For the date of the
present report the animals were vaccinated again.

Control measures
Measures applied: quarantine; movement control inside the country;
screening; vaccination in response to the outbreak(s); disinfection of
infected premises/establishment(s); no treatment of affected animals
Measures to be applied: no other measures

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type: All-Russian Research Institute for Animal
Health (FGI-ARRIAH) (national laboratory)
Species: cattle
Test: antigen (Ag) detection ELISA
Test date: 18 Mar 2011
Result: positive

Species: cattle
Test: complement fixation test (CFT)
Test date: 18 Mar 2011
Result: positive

Species: cattle
Test: gene sequencing
Test date: 21 Mar 2011
Result: positive

Species: cattle
Test: real-time PCR
Test date: 18 Mar 2011
Result: positive

Species: cattle
Test: reverse transcription-polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR)
Test date: 18 Mar 2011
Result: positive

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[A similar outbreak occurred in the exact same location last year
[2010]. It is notable that mainly cattle but one swine are involved in
this outbreak. The outbreak location is near the Mongolian border in
an anti-FMD buffer zone where vaccination is practiced.

The location of the outbreak can be seen on the map appended to the
OIE WAHID report referenced above. - Mod.PC]
